%I A397184 #15 Jul 05 2026 00:10:51
%S A397184 1,1,2,9,122,11610
%N A397184 Number of nonisomorphic metrizable betweenness relations on a set of n elements.
%C A397184 A betweenness relation on a set X is a ternary relation that captures the notion of a point lying between two other points in X. Many inequivalent notions of betweenness relations have been proposed in literature. For instance, Hedlíková requires that the axioms B(a,b,c) => B(c,b,a), B(a,b,c) & B(a,c,b) <=> b=c, B(a,b,c) & B(a,c,d) => B(b,c,d), and B(a,b,c) & B(a,c,d) => B(a,b,d) hold for all a,b,c,d in X.
%C A397184 Regardless of these inequivalent notions, by a metrizable betweenness relation on a set X, we mean a ternary relation B on X for which there exists a metric d on X so that B(x,z,y) <=> d(x,z) + d(y,z) = d(x,y) for all points x,y,z in X (see Šimko).
%C A397184 Two betweenness relations are called isomorphic if they are isomorphic as ternary relations.
%H A397184 Jarmila Hedlíková, <a href="http://dml.cz/dmlcz/101889">Ternary spaces, media, and Chebyshev sets</a>, Czechoslovak Math. J. 33 (1983), no. 3, 373-389.
%H A397184 Juraj Šimko, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/S0002-9939-99-04515-3">Metrizable and R-metrizable betweenness spaces</a>, Proc. Amer. Math. Soc. 127 (1999), no. 2, 323-325.
%H A397184 Tian Vlasic, <a href="/A397184/a397184.py.txt">Python program</a>
%e A397184 a(4)=9, as on a set of four elements, there are 9 metrizable betweenness relations up to isomorphism. If X={a,b,c,d}, a set of representatives (ignoring endpoints relations B(x,x,y) and B(x,y,y)) could be:
%e A397184   1 - no additional relations,
%e A397184   2 - B(c,b,d),
%e A397184   3 - B(a,c,d) & B(b,c,d),
%e A397184   4 - B(a,c,d) & B(b,c,d),
%e A397184   5 - B(a,c,d) & B(b,d,c),
%e A397184   6 - B(b,a,d) & B(a,d,c) & B(b,c,d),
%e A397184   7 - B(a,d,b) & B(a,d,c) & B(b,d,c),
%e A397184   8 - B(b,a,c) & B(b,a,d) & B(a,c,d) & B(b,c,d),
%e A397184   9 - B(b,a,c) & B(a,b,d) & B(a,c,d) & B(b,c,d).
%Y A397184 Cf. A395237, A364656.
%K A397184 nonn,more,hard,new
